rratives, Padilla elucidates a "story" of female agency and nationhood that extends beyond El Salvador's national borders and imaginings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican fictionxHispanic American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aIdentity (Psychology) in literature. 0aRevolutionary literature, SalvadoranxHistory and criticism. 0aSalvadoran fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen in literature. 4aArea Studies : Hispanic Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438442785423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438442785/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles